{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise (DBSCAN)\n","\n","DBSCAN is a density-based clustering algorithm. Unlike $k$-means, it does not assume that clusters have a spherical shape, nor does it partition data into manual hierarchies like hierarchical clustering. Instead, it assigns cluster labels based on **dense regions of points**.\n","\n","---\n","\n","## 1. Key Concepts & Definitions\n","\n","In DBSCAN, density is defined as the number of points within a specified radius, $\\varepsilon$ (epsilon). The algorithm categorizes each data point using two hyperparameters: **$\\varepsilon$** (radius) and **`MinPts`** (minimum neighboring points).\n","\n","Points are assigned one of three special labels:\n","\n","* **Core Point:** A point is a core point if at least a specified number (`MinPts`) of neighboring points fall within its specified radius $\\varepsilon$.\n","* **Border Point:** A point that has fewer neighbors than `MinPts` within $\\varepsilon$, but lies within the $\\varepsilon$ radius of a core point.\n","* **Noise Point:** All other points that are neither core nor border points.\n","\n","### The Two-Step Clustering Process\n","\n","1. Form a separate cluster for each core point or connected group of core points (core points are connected if they are no farther away than $\\varepsilon$).\n","2. Assign each border point to the cluster of its corresponding core point.\n","\n","---\n","\n","## 2. Advantages and Disadvantages\n","\n","### Advantages\n","\n","* **Arbitrary Shapes:** It can successfully identify complex, non-spherical structures (such as half-moon shapes) where $k$-means and agglomerative clustering fail.\n","* **Noise Filtering:** It doesn't necessarily assign every point to a cluster; it is capable of identifying and removing noise points.\n","\n","### Disadvantages\n","\n","* **Curse of Dimensionality:** As the number of features increases, the negative effects of the curse of dimensionality grow—especially when using the Euclidean distance metric.\n","* **Hyperparameter Sensitivity:** Finding a good combination of $\\varepsilon$ and `MinPts` can be highly problematic if the density differences across the dataset are large.\n","\n","> **Pro Tip:** To handle the curse of dimensionality, it is common practice to apply dimensionality reduction techniques like **PCA (Principal Component Analysis)** or **t-SNE** prior to clustering. This compresses datasets down into 2D subspaces for easier visualization and evaluation.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"D3KQghiBlnon"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 3. Python Implementation\n","\n","Below are the complete executable code segments to compare $k$-means, Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering, and DBSCAN on a half-moon dataset."],"metadata":{"id":"yRsLVQ7fmrE0"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Generate and Plot Dataset\n"],"metadata":{"id":"wRPRU65Fmw7F"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","from sklearn.datasets import make_moons\n","\n","# Create a half-moon shaped dataset\n","X, y = make_moons(n_samples=200, noise=0.05, random_state=0)\n","\n","# Visualize the unclustered data\n","plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1])\n","plt.xlabel('Feature 1')\n","plt.ylabel('Feature 2')\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":4,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":487},"id":"oRhUJBKDlnoq","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782925040073,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":170,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"0dc28e42-dcb5-441d-cbee-04e9a7ed9a5b"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Compare K-Means and Agglomerative Clustering"],"metadata":{"id":"C6X6hX4jlnos"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, AgglomerativeClustering\n","\n","# Set up side-by-side subplots\n","f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(8, 3))\n","\n","# 1. K-Means Clustering\n","km = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=0)\n","y_km = km.fit_predict(X)\n","\n","ax1.scatter(X[y_km == 0, 0], X[y_km == 0, 1], c='lightblue', edgecolor='black', marker='o', s=40, label='Cluster 1')\n","ax1.scatter(X[y_km == 1, 0], X[y_km == 1, 1], c='red', edgecolor='black', marker='s', s=40, label='Cluster 2')\n","ax1.set_title('K-means clustering')\n","ax1.set_xlabel('Feature 1')\n","ax1.set_ylabel('Feature 2')\n","\n","# 2. Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering\n","ac = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=2, metric='euclidean', linkage='complete')\n","y_ac = ac.fit_predict(X)\n","\n","ax2.scatter(X[y_ac == 0, 0], X[y_ac == 0, 1], c='lightblue', edgecolor='black', marker='o', s=40, label='Cluster 1')\n","ax2.scatter(X[y_ac == 1, 0], X[y_ac == 1, 1], c='red', edgecolor='black', marker='s', s=40, label='Cluster 2')\n","ax2.set_title('Agglomerative clustering')\n","ax2.set_xlabel('Feature 1')\n","ax2.set_ylabel('Feature 2')\n","\n","plt.legend()\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 800x300 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":5,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":307},"id":"Q6u7uCMplnos","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782925040625,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":554,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"c46963eb-4dc4-4717-e544-13472af386f7"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### DBSCAN Clustering"],"metadata":{"id":"yvLsJVonlnot"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN\n","\n","# 3. DBSCAN Clustering\n","db = DBSCAN(eps=0.2, min_samples=5, metric='euclidean')\n","y_db = db.fit_predict(X)\n","\n","plt.scatter(X[y_db == 0, 0], X[y_db == 0, 1], c='lightblue', edgecolor='black', marker='o', s=40, label='Cluster 1')\n","plt.scatter(X[y_db == 1, 0], X[y_db == 1, 1], c='red', edgecolor='black', marker='s', s=40, label='Cluster 2')\n","\n","plt.xlabel('Feature 1')\n","plt.ylabel('Feature 2')\n","plt.title('DBSCAN clustering on the half-moon shaped dataset')\n","plt.legend()\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":6,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":487},"id":"h9Een9-Flnot","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782925040701,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":75,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"44102b5e-e446-4e02-a0da-2acd892d4d22"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 4. Note on Alternative Paradigms: Graph-Based Clustering\n","\n","Beyond prototype-based ($k$-means), hierarchical, and density-based (DBSCAN) methods, there is a fourth major family: **Graph-based clustering**.\n","\n","The most prominent algorithms in this family are **Spectral Clustering** algorithms. These utilize the eigenvectors of a similarity or distance matrix to establish relationships and find clusters within highly intricate structures."],"metadata":{"id":"xd9QsuXKlnot"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}